<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911209-0123</DOCNO><DOCID>911209-0123.</DOCID><HL>   Two Securities Traders   And One Lawyer Face   Tax Fraud Indictment</HL><DATE>12/09/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   TAXES</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>SECURITIES REGULATIONS AND ENFORCEMENT (RGU)SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><NS>SECURITIES REGULATION (RGU)TAXES (TAX)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- Two New York securities traders and theirattorney were indicted on 16 charges of tax evasion, filingfalse tax returns and conspiring to defraud the U.S.   The indictment in the Eastern district of New York chargedthat the two traders, Fergus Sloan and Jury Matt Hansen, whowere equal partners in Fermat Management Associates, NewYork, diverted profits to a shell Panamanian corporation,Graycliff International S.A.</LP><TEXT>   The indictment also charged the two traders with receivingkickbacks from stock brokers in exchange for their continuedbusiness and failing to declare the kickbacks as income ontheir tax returns.   The U.S. attorney described their attorney, Peter Schmidt,as a &quot;prominent New York attorney who disappeared in 1988following allegations by clients that he had stolen moneyfrom them.&quot; The indictment alleged that he assisted the twotraders in the scheme.   If convicted, Messrs. Hansen and Sloan face up to 70 yearsin jail and may be fined up to $250,000 on each of thecounts. Mr. Schmidt faces five years in jail and a $250,000fine. None of the men could be reached for comment.   The two traders are also the subject of a pending civilcase brought by the Securities and Exchange Commission. In1989, the SEC's New York regional office charged the men andthe companies with opening 250 accounts at over 100brokerdealers in 76 fictitious names. The defendants havedenied that they conducted any improper stock transactions ormisled brokers about the trades.</TEXT></DOC>